Phase 1: Viewer-First UX (PathCollab-ri96)

## Background

During development, state can get into inconsistent configurations. A 'Reset State' button provides quick recovery without manual localStorage clearing.

## Task

Implement state reset:

1. **Reset function**:
```typescript
const resetAppState = () => {
    // Clear localStorage
    const keysToRemove = [
        'session_token',
        'last_slide_id',
        'sidebar_collapsed',
        'tips_dismissed',
        'layer_visibility',
        // ...
    ];
    keysToRemove.forEach(key => localStorage.removeItem(key));

    // Clear session storage
    sessionStorage.clear();

    // Disconnect WebSocket
    wsConnection?.close();

    // Reload page
    window.location.reload();
};
```

2. **UI in Debug panel**:
```tsx
<button
    onClick={() => {
        if (confirm('Reset all app state? This will reload the page.')) {
            resetAppState();
        }
    }}
    className="w-full mt-4 px-3 py-2 text-sm text-red-600 border border-red-200 rounded hover:bg-red-50"
>
    Reset App State
</button>
```

3. **Items to reset**:
   - localStorage keys (session, preferences)
   - sessionStorage
   - WebSocket connection
   - In-memory state (via page reload)

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Button in Debug section
- [ ] Confirmation before reset
- [ ] All local storage cleared
- [ ] Page reloads after reset
- [ ] App starts fresh after reset
- [ ] Warning about data loss

## Why This Matters

Quick reset:
- Speeds up development cycles
- Recovers from stuck states
- Tests fresh user experience
- Simplifies debugging

