Phase 4: Debuggability (PathCollab-3tel)

## Background

Currently, presence updates (cursors at 30Hz) and viewport updates (10Hz) may have separate broadcast mechanisms. A unified tick loop simplifies the architecture and makes timing predictable.

## Task

Create a single server tick loop:

1. **Tick loop design**:
   - Single async task per session
   - Runs at highest frequency needed (30Hz = 33ms interval)
   - Each tick: aggregate and broadcast pending updates
   - Viewport broadcast every 3rd tick (10Hz)

2. **Aggregation logic**:
   - Cursor updates: collect all since last tick, send delta
   - Viewport: only send if changed since last broadcast
   - Batch processing for efficiency

3. **Implementation**:
```rust
async fn session_tick_loop(session_id: SessionId, state: AppState) {
    let mut interval = tokio::time::interval(Duration::from_millis(33)); // 30Hz
    let mut tick_count = 0u32;

    loop {
        interval.tick().await;
        tick_count += 1;

        // Always: presence delta
        if let Some(delta) = state.get_presence_delta(&session_id) {
            state.broadcast(&session_id, ServerMessage::Presence(delta));
        }

        // Every 3rd tick (10Hz): viewport
        if tick_count % 3 == 0 {
            if let Some(viewport) = state.get_presenter_viewport(&session_id) {
                state.broadcast(&session_id, ServerMessage::Viewport(viewport));
            }
        }
    }
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Single tick loop per active session
- [ ] Presence broadcasts at 30Hz
- [ ] Viewport broadcasts at 10Hz
- [ ] Loop starts when session created
- [ ] Loop stops when session ends
- [ ] CPU usage reasonable (< 1% per session)

## Technical Details

**Starting the loop**:
```rust
impl SessionManager {
    pub async fn create_session(&self, slide_id: &str) -> Result<Session> {
        let session = Session::new(slide_id);

        // Start tick loop
        let handle = tokio::spawn(session_tick_loop(
            session.id.clone(),
            self.state.clone()
        ));
        self.tick_handles.insert(session.id.clone(), handle);

        Ok(session)
    }
}
```

**Stopping the loop**:
```rust
impl SessionManager {
    pub async fn end_session(&self, session_id: &SessionId) {
        if let Some(handle) = self.tick_handles.remove(session_id) {
            handle.abort();
        }
        // ... cleanup
    }
}
```

## Why This Matters

A single tick loop:
- Makes timing predictable and debuggable
- Reduces race conditions
- Simplifies broadcast logic
- Makes it easy to adjust rates

